Package com.phunware.engagement.log

  • Interface Summary 
    Interface Description
    Logger
    A Logger handles log messages and errors at different log levels. Implementations of this class need to be performant, as log messages can be sent on the main thread and in tight loops. If the Logger implementation needs any sort File I/O or network related calls, it should manage it's own thread and pass the calls accordingly.
  • Class Summary 
    Class Description
    CompositeLogger
    Support delegating log messages to a collection of child Loggers.
    LogLogger
    Writes log messages to Android's logcat. This will be on by default in dev.
    Logging
    API for sending log output. Generally, use the Log.v() Log.d() Log.i() Log.w() Log.e() and Log.wtf() methods. The order in terms of verbosity, from least to most is TERRIBLE_FAILURE, ERROR, WARN, INFO, DEBUG, VERBOSE. Verbose should never be compiled into an application except during development. Tip: A good convention is to declare a TAG constant in your class: private static final String TAG = "LocationManagerImpl"; and use that in subsequent calls to the log methods.
    VoidLogger
    This is a no-op log implementation. It can be used in production environments to drop all log messages.
